-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ§  What are Lists in React?

In React, we often need to display **multiple items dynamically**, such as:

* Todo items
* Products
* Users
* Comments
* Messages

React renders lists using the **map() method**.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”· Rendering Lists using map()

```jsx
function UserList() {
  const users = ["Amit", "Riya", "John"];

  return (
    <ul>
      {users.map((user, index) => (
        <li key={index}>{user}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

ğŸ“Œ `map()` converts array into JSX elements

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”· Rendering List of Objects

```jsx
function ProductList() {
  const products = [
    { id: 1, name: "Laptop" },
    { id: 2, name: "Phone" }
  ];

  return (
    <ul>
      {products.map(product => (
        <li key={product.id}>
          {product.name}
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

ğŸ“Œ Always use **unique id as key**

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”‘ What is a Key in React?

A **key** is a special attribute used by React to:

* Identify list items uniquely
* Track changes
* Improve rendering performance
* Optimize Virtual DOM updates

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ§  Why Keys are Important?

When list updates:

* React compares old & new Virtual DOM
* Keys help React identify:

  * Which item changed
  * Which item added
  * Which item removed

Without keys â†’ React may re-render entire list âŒ

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âŒ Bad Practice

```jsx
{items.map((item, index) => (
  <li key={index}>{item}</li>
))}
```

ğŸ“Œ Using index as key can cause issues when:

* Items are reordered
* Items are added/removed

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âœ… Best Practice

```jsx
{items.map(item => (
  <li key={item.id}>{item.name}</li>
))}
```

âœ” Use unique ID
âœ” Stable key

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”„ Example: Dynamic List with State

```jsx
import { useState } from "react";

function TodoApp() {
  const [todos, setTodos] = useState([]);

  const addTodo = () => {
    const newTodo = {
      id: Date.now(),
      text: "New Task"
    };
    setTodos([...todos, newTodo]);
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <button onClick={addTodo}>Add</button>

      <ul>
        {todos.map(todo => (
          <li key={todo.id}>{todo.text}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
}
```

ğŸ“Œ Proper keys prevent rendering issues

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ§  When Can You Use Index as Key?

Only when:

* List is static
* Items never change
* No reordering
* No filtering

Otherwise âŒ avoid it

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ” Conditional List Rendering

```jsx
{items.length > 0 ? (
  items.map(item => <li key={item.id}>{item.name}</li>)
) : (
  <p>No Items Found</p>
)}
```

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âš ï¸ Common Mistakes

âŒ Missing key attribute
âŒ Using random values as key
âŒ Using index incorrectly
âŒ Duplicate keys

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ’¡ Best Practices

âœ” Use unique & stable keys
âœ” Prefer database IDs
âœ” Keep list rendering clean
âœ” Extract list items into components

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”· Extracting List Item as Component

```jsx
function User({ user }) {
  return <li>{user.name}</li>;
}

function UserList({ users }) {
  return (
    <ul>
      {users.map(user => (
        <User key={user.id} user={user} />
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

ğŸ“Œ Key should be on parent element

